<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 5.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Communication</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>5K1.</strong> Principles - verbal, written, nonverbal.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The World Health Organization suggests six principles for effective communication:<sup>1</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>Accessible</strong>: Identify all available communication channels and compare their capacities to reach priority audiences. Using the right mix of channels helps inform audiences with the information they need to make  decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>Actionable</strong>: Understand the knowledge, attitudes and behaviors of your target audience to create messages that address challenges and encourage decision-makers to take the recommended steps.</li>
      <li><strong>Credible</strong>: Use every opportunity to reinforce your trustworthiness, including stressing technical accuracy and transparency, so that your recommendations become the basis for health decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>Relevant</strong>: Help decision-makers understand that there is a health risk for themselves or those in their care, that the risk could be severe, and that undertaking recommended actions will reduce that risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Timely</strong>: Make information, advice and guidance available in a timely way, so audiences have the information they need when they need it in order to make appropriate health decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>Understandable</strong>: Provide key audiences that are not technical experts with information that is easy to understand so they comprehend the health risks and take appropriate actions.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="https://www.who.int/communicating-for-health/principles/en/">A more detailed explanation of these principles is accessible at the WHO website</a>.</p>
	  <p>Communication can take place verbally, nonverbally, or in written form. Each type of communication has its own unique considerations, but they all share the common goal of effectively conveying messages and fostering understanding.</p>
	  <p>Verbal Communication Principles</p>

<ul><li>Clarity: Use clear, concise language to convey your message.</li>
<li>Active listening: Pay attention to the speaker and provide feedback.</li>
<li>Tone of voice: Adjust your tone to suit the context and emotion of the message.</li>
<li>Pacing: Speak at an appropriate speed and use pauses effectively.</li>
<li>Articulation: Pronounce words clearly and accurately.
<li>Adaptability: Adjust your language and style to your audience.</li>
<li>Empathy: Show understanding and sensitivity to the listener's perspective.</li>
<li>Questioning: Use appropriate questions to gather information and clarify understanding.</li></ul>

	  <p>Written Communication Principles</p>

<ul><li>Clarity and conciseness: Express ideas clearly and efficiently.</li>
<li>Structure: Organize content logically with clear paragraphs and sections.</li>
<li>Audience awareness: Tailor your writing style and content to your readers.</li>
<li>Accuracy: Ensure information, grammar, and punctuation are correct.</li>
<li>Tone: Use an appropriate tone for your audience and purpose.</li>
<li>Revision: Review and edit your work for improvement.</li>
<li>Formatting: Use layout, font, and visual elements to enhance readability.</li>
<li>Coherence: Ensure ideas flow smoothly and logically throughout the text.</li></ul>

<p>Nonverbal Communication Principles</p>

<ul>
  <li>Body language: Be aware of posture, gestures and facial expressions.</li>
<li>Eye contact: Maintain appropriate eye contact to show engagement.</li>
<li>Proxemics: Respect personal space and  norms regarding distance.</li>
<li>Paralanguage: Pay attention to voice qualities like pitch, volume and speed.</li>
<li>Touch: Use touch appropriately based on context and community norms.</li>
<li>Appearance: Consider how your clothing and grooming affect communication.</li>
<li>Environment: Be aware of how the physical setting influences interaction.</li>
<li>Time management: Respect others&rsquo; time and be punctual.</li></ul>
</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comment-1"></i> <strong>5K2.</strong> Communication challenges.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Every person possesses a unique set of abilities and aptitudes. You will not communicate successfully with someone if they receive your message but do not understand it. You can take steps to improve the chances that others will understand what you are trying to communicate.</p>
    <p><strong>Use Plain Language</strong>. Plain language is characterized by:<sup>2</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Common, everyday words except for necessary technical terms</li>
      <li>Personal pronouns (&ldquo;we&rdquo; and &ldquo;you&rdquo;)</li>
      <li>Active voice</li>
      <li>Logical organization</li>
      <li>An easy-to-read format, including bullets, tables and ample whitespace.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Using simple, easy to understand language is essential for communicating successfully with a general audience whose literacy level is unknown. However, even highly educated professionals appreciate reading information presented in this way.<sup>3</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Educate Yourself About Community Norms and Boundaries</strong></p>
    <p>Communication rules can differ between community groups. Members of those groups learn its communication rules, such as who communicates with whom, when and where something may be communicated, and what to communicate about. Frequently, those within a community also learn one or more languages that facilitate communication within the group.<sup>4</sup> But language can be a challenge to successful communication. When people and organizations try to use languages or jargon specific to their group in other contexts, communication can fail.</p>
    <p>One qualitative study of Australian health care professionals gathered many examples of how the lack of community knowledge had resulted in communication challenges for patients, students and colleagues.<sup>5</sup> In response to this, participants said that they had looked for opportunities to attend community awareness seminars and workshops to understand  boundaries and certain behavioral norms.</p>
    <p><strong>Be Prepared for Language Differences</strong></p>
    <p>Language differences are an obvious communication barrier. They make it more difficult for people from various backgrounds to communicate, and for those populations to make informed decisions, since it  redues the amount of information that individuals can draw upon.<sup>6</sup></p>
    <p>In 2016, more than 65 million U.S. residents (more than one in five) spoke a language other than English at home. The largest portion of that group spoke Spanish, followed by Indo-European languages (such as French, German, and Russian), Chinese (including Mandarin, Cantonese, and other dialects), Vietnamese, Tagalog, and Arabic.<sup>7</sup></p>
    <p>Even when steps are taken to provide translation services, MCH professionals must take care to ensure that communication has been successful. A study conducted at a pediatric outpatient clinic found that of the health care visits where interpreters were assisting patients, there were still an average of 31 errors in each clinical encounter.<sup>6</sup> </p>
    <p><strong>Avoid Technical Terms and Jargon</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Jargon is a word or phrase that has a specific meaning inside a profession but that loses or changes that meaning when used outside the profession.<sup>8</sup> </li>
      <li>Take care to minimize or avoid acronyms. They can save time, but can alienate readers who are unfamiliar with them. </li>
      <li>Avoid words that have alternate meanings outside of MCH, and words that are specific to your profession.</li>
    </ul>    
  </div>
 <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comment-1"></i> <strong>5K3.</strong> Responsiveness to various backgrounds when communicating with individuals/communities.</button>
  <div class="panel">
  <p>Communication that takes  differences into account is essential for effective health care delivery, as it:</p>
<ol>
<li>Enhances understanding and fosters shared decision-making: Community beliefs and practices influence health behaviors. Studies show that communication that acknowledges and respects community values leads to better understanding of medical information and facilitates shared decision-making between health care providers and patients.<sup>9</sup> This is particularly important in MCH, where decisions around prenatal care, birth plans, and child development can be emotionally charged and  influenced.</li>
<li>Builds trust and reduces health differences: Insensitive communication can create a barrier to care. Research demonstrates that certain populations are less likely to utilize preventive services or seek prenatal care if they feel misunderstood by health care providers.<sup>10</sup> By using  responsive communication techniques, MCH professionals can build trust with patients, leading to increased health care utilization and improved health outcomes.</li>
<li>Tailors communication strategies: Effective communication goes beyond language translation. Responsive communication involves tailoring communication styles, considering nonverbal cues, and acknowledging community preferences. For instance, some communities/families prioritize collective decision-making, while others place emphasis on individual autonomy. Recognizing these nuances allows health care professionals to adapt their communication approach.<sup>11</sup></li></ol>  
  </div>

	  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comment-1"></i> <strong>5K4.</strong>Health literacy to ensuring fair access.</button>
	  <div class="panel">
  <p>Health literacy — the ability to access, understand, evaluate, and use health information — is a cornerstone of fair access to information and services, enabling individuals to navigate the complexities of health care, ultimately improving health outcomes for mothers and children.</p>
<p><strong>Encouraging informed decisions: </strong>Strong health literacy equips individuals to make informed decisions about their health and the health of their children. Studies have shown that mothers with higher health literacy are more likely to:
<ul><li>Attend prenatal care visits regularly: This allows for early detection and management of potential complications during pregnancy, leading to improved birth outcomes.<sup>12</sup></li>
<li>Follow immunization schedules: Timely vaccinations protect children from preventable diseases, ensuring their healthy development.<sup>13</sup></li>
<li>Practice healthy behaviors during pregnancy: Behaviors like maintaining a healthy diet and avoiding smoking contribute significantly to a child's well-being.<sup>14</sup></li></ul>
<p><strong>Bridging the  access gap: </strong>Low health literacy disproportionately affects low-income, specific populations and individuals with limited education. This creates a significant barrier to accessing and comprehending essential MCH information and services. Research suggests that targeted interventions aimed at improving health literacy can effectively reduce these variations in health outcomes. For instance, providing educational materials in clear, concise language and offering approachable and sensitive communication strategies can empower individuals to understand complex medical concepts and make informed choices about their care.<sup>15</sup></p>
<p><strong>Effective communication and shared decision-making:</strong> Health literacy fosters effective communication with health care providers. Mothers with strong health literacy skills are better equipped to:</p>
<ul><li>Ask questions and clarify any doubts they may have regarding their health or their child's health.</li>
<li>Understand medical information presented by health care providers, allowing them to participate actively in discussions about treatment options.</li>
<li>Engage in shared decision-making, collaborating with providers to develop a care plan that aligns with their values and preferences.<sup>10</sup></ul>

  
</div>
	  
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-flow-tree"></i> <strong>5S1.</strong> Share/communicate with individuals/groups.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Verbal communication skills are essential for MCH professionals. You should be able to speak effectively in a variety of circumstances, from formal presentations at academic gatherings to more casual interactions with members of the public during outreach activities or meetings with other staff members. </p>
    <p>Suggestions for effective verbal communication:<sup>16</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Define your audience</strong>: Will you be speaking formally to a group of peers? Informally to a community group? </li>
      <li><strong>Define your purpos</strong>e: Are you teaching a class or delivering a training session? Are you sharing research results at a conference? Are you part of a panel discussion that will be moderated?</li>
      <li><strong>Speaking is different than writing</strong>. Regardless of audience, talking about your work is very different than writing about it. Try to think of how your audience will perceive your talk.</li>
      <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t read from your slides</strong>. Use notes or cues, such as written reminders or numbers, to guide you through your talk or provide just enough content on your slides to guide you through.</li>
      <li><strong>Avoid slides with excessive text</strong>. This is distracting. Do use interesting photos and clear diagrams that explain processes.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-language"></i> <strong>5S2.</strong>Health literacy to ensuring fair access.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Suggestions for clear, effective writing:<sup>17</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Make the purpose and usefulness of the material immediately obvious. Use the title and other upfront text to make clear to readers what the material is about, who it is for, and how to use it. </li>
      <li>In choosing which content to include, be guided by the readers&rsquo; interests, knowledge, and needs (which may be different from your own). Address readers&rsquo; issues and concerns, as well as areas of possible confusion.</li>
      <li>Show awareness of and respect for the different backgrounds of intended readers. Choose content that is  appropriate for the intended readers, reflecting and responding to differences in their experiences and situations.</li>
      <li>Repeat new concepts and summarize the most important points. All readers need time to absorb new information. Repetition helps them remember it.</li>
      <li>Make sure that the information is accurate and up to date. Check facts.</li>
      <li>Involve subject-matter experts from the beginning and have reviewers check on accuracy. Proofread carefully.</li>
      <li>Limit the information to an amount that is reasonable for the intended readers. Especially for less-skilled readers, too much text can be overwhelming. If the material is too long, consider other ways to package it. When condensing information, don&rsquo;t oversimplify or drop essential examples and explanations. </li>
      <li>Identify the organization that produced the material, and include a publication date and contact information. Including the date will help remind you when it&rsquo;s time to update the information.</li>
    </ul>
  <p>Public health professionals should be able to contribute original research to add to the body of knowledge that advances the field. The final, critical step in any research is to write about it in a scholarly paper submitted for peer review and publication in a journal.</p>
  <p>Every journal article is expected to have a title, abstract, introduction, methods, results, discussion, and references. Known as the IMRAD format, it is a scientific standard for publication.<sup>18</sup></p>
	<p>Tips for writing about research:<sup>19</sup></p>
      <ul><li>Writing should be clear and straightforward, even though journal articles are generally read by an educated audience.</li>
      <li>Define acronyms used in the text, and minimize their use, if possible.</li>
     <li>Explain statistical methods.</li>
     <li>Present results with charts.</li>
     <li>When formatting text and references, be sure to follow the requirements that a journal maintains for articles submitted for publication.</li></ul>
  <p>Tips for presenting research:<sup>20</sup></p>
     <ul><li>Know your audience and create a presentation that engages them.</li>
     <li>Present your information clearly and concisely to ensure that the main message is not lost in too much detail.</li>
     <li>Ensure that your main points are memorable.</li>
     <li>Craft a logical flow to your presentation &mdash; beginning, middle, and end with a clear take-home message.</li>
     <li>Add humor and anecdotes, but don’t exceed your ability to be funny or tell stories.</li>
     <li>Practice and time your presentation, then stick with what you’ve practiced.</li>
    <li>Use visuals to support what you’re staying, but don’t overuse them.</li>
    <li>Provide appropriate acknowledgments of others’ contributions.</li>
    <li>If possible, review video of your presentation to fine-tune your delivery.</li></ul>
	  
     <p><a href="http://jphe.amegroups.com/article/view/4265/5102">Read more guidance on how to write a research article</a>.</p>
     <p><a href="https://library-cuanschutz.libguides.com/c.php?g=259527&p=1732691">View resources for public health presentation and Powerpoint skills</a> from the University of Colorado Strauss Health Sciences Library.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-thumbs-up"></i> <strong>5S3.</strong> Active listening for nonverbal cues.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Face-to-face communication takes place through what is said verbally and what is communicated nonverbally via body language and other cues.</p>
    <p>Nonverbal communication can play five roles:<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Repetition</strong>: It reiterates and can reinforce the message you&rsquo;re making verbally.</li>
      <li><strong>Contradiction</strong>: It can counter the message you&rsquo;re trying to convey, alerting your listener that you may not be telling the truth.</li>
      <li><strong>Substitution</strong>: It can take the place of a verbal message. Frequently, facial expressions convey a stronger message than words can.</li>
      <li><strong>Complementing</strong>: It may bolster or complement your verbal message. </li>
      <li><strong>Accenting</strong>: It may emphasize a verbal message. If you pound a table while making a point it makes clear how important you regard your message to be.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Understanding and decoding body language is essential to communication. Some nonverbal signals to look for (and be aware of in yourself):<sup>19</sup> </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Eye contact</strong>: Is the person making eye contact? If so, is it overly intense or just right?</li>
      <li><strong>Facial expression</strong>: What is their face showing? Is it masklike and unexpressive, or emotionally present and filled with interest?</li>
      <li><strong>Tone of voice</strong>: Does the person&rsquo;s voice project warmth, confidence, and interest, or is it strained and blocked?</li>
      <li><strong>Posture and gesture</strong>: Is their body relaxed or stiff and immobile? Are their shoulders tense and raised, or relaxed?</li>
      <li><strong>Touch</strong>: Is there any physical contact? Is it appropriate to the situation? Does it make you feel uncomfortable?</li>
      <li><strong>Intensity</strong>: Does the person seem flat, cool, and disinterested, or over-the-top and melodramatic?</li>
      <li><strong>Timing and place</strong>: Is there an easy flow of information back and forth? Do nonverbal responses come too quickly or too slowly?</li>
      <li><strong>Sounds</strong>: Do you hear sounds that indicate interest, caring or concern from the person? </li>
  </ul>
 
    <p>Active listening means allowing a speaker to fully express themselves, withholding judgment on what they say and demonstrating a genuine interest in the speaker. Frequently, you will be listening for what is not said as much as what is.<sup>20</sup></p>
    <p>Complement active listening with open, candid discussion. Active listening alone often isn&rsquo;t enough: you must be prepared to be influenced by what you hear. Be genuine or you may run into problems later.</p>
    <p>Active listening skills:<sup>20</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Define terms to promote clarity</strong>: Clarify technical terms and jargon; discuss different possible meanings. </li>
      <li><strong>Repeat/paraphrase</strong>: Repeat back what the other person is saying, using some of their words, to verify that you understand what they are saying.</li>
      <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t interrupt</strong>: Give people space to talk freely. Don&rsquo;t assume that silence means agreement – build in time for people to say all that they want to and prepare questions to elicit their views if they are not immediately forthcoming.</li>
      <li><strong>Listen &ldquo;between the lines&rdquo;</strong>: Try to &ldquo;hear&rdquo; the speaker on all levels -- words, feelings, assumptions, values, wishes and fears. Use your instincts to consider if this person means what they say. Be alert to how language or body language can indicate feelings.</li>
      <li><strong>Don&rsquo;t rush to fill silences</strong>: Silence can enable the speaker to think through or reflect more deeply on what they are telling you. It can enable them to gain additional insights into their views, or make links between ideas. Sometimes silence can reflect emotional discomfort; providing this space can enable someone to say how they are really feeling.</li>
      <li><strong>Reflect impressions back</strong>: You can check observations with simple statements – e.g., &ldquo;If I were in your shoes, I might be thinking…&rdquo; and see if people agree. To develop trust, show genuine interest, provide a safe environment and listen openly. </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
    
      <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>5S4.</strong> Tailor information for audience.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>MCH professionals should know how to tailor their messages to successfully communicate with various stakeholder groups. These may include consumers, policymakers, clinicians, and the public.<sup>21</sup></p>
    <p>Generally, a message should convey a complete idea in approximately two sentences and frame an issue for its intended audience. Consider the following:<sup>21</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>What do I want my intended audience to know?</li>
      <li>Why should this audience know about this?</li>
      <li>Why is this important to them?</li>
      <li>What do I want my audience to do as a result of the message: take action, tell others?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Based on the answers to the previous questions, create a strong message by doing the following:<sup>21</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Be specific in what you are asking the target audience to do.</li>
      <li>Using what you know about your audience&rsquo;s priorities, explain how they will benefit from acting upon what you&rsquo;re telling them.</li>
      <li>Provide evidence of why what you are telling them is important, either through data or a compelling example.</li>
      <li>Use compelling images or analogies to make your message memorable.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  
 
 
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comments-1"></i> <strong>5S5.</strong> Employ all communication skills.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><strong>Disseminating Information in a Crisis</strong>. It is essential for MCH professionals to be prepared to communicate on their organization&rsquo;s behalf in the event of a crisis. They may find themselves having to email community partners, take calls from members of the public or the media, or speak at a hostile public meeting. </p>
    <p>MCH professionals and others involved in public health use data to inform their responses to a situation. But members of the public frequently have an emotional response. This can affect how they perceive risk and impede their ability to process information and respond appropriately. As a result, in a crisis situation MCH professionals should:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Have a plan</strong>:<sup>21</sup>
        <ul>
          <li>Develop a response protocol in advance</li>
          <li>Designate a spokesperson</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      <li><strong>Craft a message</strong>:<sup>21, 22</sup>
        <ul>
          <li>Acknowledge and legitimize the emotions people feel</li>
          <li>Use simple, understandable terms, without jargon</li>
          <li>Tell the truth; if you don&rsquo;t know something, say so</li>
          <li>Explain what you do know and what you are investigating</li>
          <li>Do not use humor</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>During the crisis</strong>:<sup>21, 22</sup>
        <ul>
          <li>Respond as quickly as possible; account for the speed of social media </li>
          <li>Keep the message consistent across your organization, from the website to the phones</li>
          <li>Be respectful and empathetic</li>
          <li>Listen to the concerns of the public</li>
          <li>Offer ways people can take action to channel their fear</li>
          <li>Schedule regular updates throughout the crisis cycle    </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      </ul>
    <p><strong>Relaying Difficult News</strong>. It can be especially challenging to deliver bad news to another individual or group. MCH professionals can prepare for the eventuality of doing this by remembering the six step strategy developed for oncologists known as SPIKES. SPIKES is a mnemonic for:<sup>23, 24</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Setting</strong>: Determine where and how you will break the news
        <ul>
          <li>Allot adequate time</li>
          <li>Create privacy</li>
          <li>Use appropriate non-verbal communication, such as eye contact or touching a hand or arm</li>
          <li>Determine who else should be present</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Perception</strong>: Ask open-ended questions to understand the person&rsquo;s perception of the situation.
        <ul>
          <li>Correct misinformation </li>
          <li>Tailor the bad news to what is understood</li>
          <li>Gauge denial</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Invitation for Information</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Find out what and how much they want to know</li>
          <li>Offer choices for how you can deliver information (directly or to a relative or friend)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Knowledge</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Provide a warning or main goal for the information that comes next</li>
          <li>Use language appropriate to the person&rsquo;s level of understanding</li>
          <li>Give information in small chunks</li>
          <li>Assess the person&rsquo;s response and empathize</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Explore Emotions and Empathize</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Assess the person&rsquo;s response and empathize</li>
          <li>Convey empathy through:
            <ul>
              <li>Encouraging description of feelings</li>
              <li>Acknowledgement/reflection</li>
              <li>Legitimization</li>
              <li>Partnership</li>
              <li>Support</li>
              <li>Sensitive silence</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          </ul>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Strategy and Summary</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Outline immediate options and information choices</li>
          <li>Indicate what options exist for next steps</li>
          <li>Assess the person&rsquo;s understanding of the situation and what will happen next</li>
          <li>Assess the person&rsquo;s social support and need to communicate with others</li>
          <li>Assess the person&rsquo;s present emotional state</li>
          <li>Provide a means of contact for further questions</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Explaining Opportunities and Risks for Health Promotion and Disease Prevention</strong>. Health promotion and disease prevention activities focus on keeping people healthy. They address risk factors for disease and encourage healthy behaviors in people. They frequently focus on the economic, social, and political conditions in which people are born, grow, and live that affect health status.</p>
    <p>Communication plays a large role in raising awareness of health promotion and disease prevention. Effective health communication and social marketing strategies include the following components:<sup>25</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Use research to create and deploy messages to the intended audience.</li>
      <li>Understand the  context for the messages and ensure they match.</li>
      <li>Consider characteristics of the target audience such as health literacy and tech savviness.</li>
      <li>Develop materials and activities appropriate to the audience and message, like brochures, billboards, newspaper articles, television broadcasts, radio commercials, public service announcements, newsletters, pamphlets, videos, digital tools, case studies, group discussions, health fairs, field trips, and workbooks. </li>
    </ul>
    </div>
    
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-alt"></i> <strong>5S6.</strong> Summarize complex information for varied audiences.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>When summarizing complex information, knowing the health literacy level of your audience is key. However, even subject matter experts appreciate clear, simple language when reading.<sup>3</sup> </p>
    <p>Several steps may help in the summarizing process:<sup>26</sup></p>
    <ol>
      <li>State information as simply as possible, minimizing jargon and acronyms.</li>
      <li>If appropriate, use metaphors to help explain a topic</li>
      <li>Use active verbs</li>
      <li>Divide content into chunks</li>
      <li>Assign descriptive headers to each section of copy</li>
      <li>Consider using bullets or numbered lists to present information</li>
      <li>Use diagrams or other graphics to help explain </li>
    </ol>
    <p>Word and sentence length are two indicators commonly evaluated to determine a text&rsquo;s readability. Research suggests that effective written communication should take into account more factors than just these two.<sup>27</sup> Short words are not always easy to understand, and long sentences are not always hard to understand. Approach the simplification process carefully to ensure that your text is readable.</p>
  </div>
    
  
